s book gives a timely account of prominent programmes such as 24, Buffy the Vampire Slayer, ER, The Sopranos and The West Wing and explores their influential position within the television industry. Divided into the areas of history, aesthetics and reception, the text provides an illuminating overview of an increasingly hybrid television studies discipline. Chapters consider the formal and aesthetic elements in the contemporary television serial through approaches ranging from those concerned with issues of gender and sexuality, national identity, and reception to industry history and textual analysis. The book also includes British examples of 'quality' serial television emphasizing not only their cultural specificity but also the transnational context in which these programmes operate.Key FeaturesSection introductions provide student-friendly explanations of the various approaches and methodologies employed in the book Chapters are written by an international team of experts in the field of television studies Ideal for use as a textbook on courses in contemporary television taught at undergraduate level"  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aTelevision seriesxHistory and criticism. 4aFilm, Media & Cultural Studies. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh1 aCardwell, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClark, J. Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFeuer, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFreedman, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHammond, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHills, Matt, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJacobs, Jason, econtributor.4ctb4http